SIMPLE: rankle
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rankle
<hw>Ran"kle</hw> <pr>(r⟦acr⟧⟦nsm⟧"k'l)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Rankled</conjf>
<pr>(-k'ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Rankling</conjf>
<pr>(-kl⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <er>Rank</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become, or be, rank; to grow
rank or strong; to be inflamed; to fester; -- used literally and
figuratively.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A malady that burns and <qex>rankles</qex> inward.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This would have left a <qex>rankling</qex> wound in the hearts of
the people.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To produce a festering or inflamed effect; to cause
a sore; -- used literally and figuratively; <as>as, a splinter
<ex>rankles</ex> in the flesh; the words <ex>rankled</ex> in his
bosom.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rankle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rankle
<hw>Ran"kle</hw> <pr>(r⟦acr⟧⟦nsm⟧"k'l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To
cause to fester; to make sore; to inflame.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rankly</ent>⟦br⟧
